dictionary.definition: A large European scinoid fish (Scina umbra or S. aquila),having white bloodless flesh. It is valued as a food fish. [Writtenalso maigre.]
The larva or grub of a large South American beetle (Calandrapalmarum), which lives in the pith of palm trees and sugar cane. Itis eaten by the natives, and esteemed a delicacy.
The act of postponing; a deferring, or putting off, to a futuretime; a temporary delay. Macaulay.
Pertaining to, or derived from, or designating, a complexorganic acid found in the products of different members of the Pepperfamily, and extracted as a yellowish crystalline substance.
Hydroxy benzene. Same as Phenol.
Sophistical.
Pertaining to, or derived from, the nutmeg (Myristica).Specifically, designating an acid found in nutmeg oil and otoba fat,and extracted as a white crystalline waxy substance.
Having a large admixture of small pebbles or gravel; -- said ofa soil. Gardner.
Burdensome; troublesome. [Obs.] Chaucer.
The leatherback.
The myristate of glycerin, -- found as a vegetable fat innutmeg butter, etc.
See Hoarding, 2. Smart.
See Mistletoe.
A small landau.
To raise little bladders or blisters upon; to inflame andseparate the cuticle of; to blister. Wiseman.
Severely; rigidly; sternly.A doctrine austerely logical. Macaulay.
A South American monkey, the ursine howler (Mycetes ursinus).See Howler, n., 2.
The top end of a timber, rising above the gunwale, and servingfor belaying ropes, etc.; -- called also kevel head.
One who, or that which, quilts.
That part of a fungus which is covered with the hymenium.
Erratic.-- Er*rat"ic*al*ly, adv.-- Er*rat"ic*al*ness, n.
A mineral consisting of sulphate of lead, occurring eithermassive or in long slender prisms, of a greenish white or gray color.
Payment in advance.
Having the quality of associating; tending or leading toassociation; as, the associative faculty. Hugh Miller.
To unlink; to disunite; to separate. [R.] Tennyson.
The upper faceted portion of a brilliant-cut diamond, whichprojects from the setting and occupies the zone between the girdleand the table. See Brilliant, n.
To adopt (a person who is his own master).
An accomplice; a "pal." [Obs.]There is no thief without a louk. Chaucer.
Containing an appeal.An appellatory libel ought to contain the name of the partyappellant. Ayliffe.
A little hillock; a knoll. Ainsworth.
One who, or that which, blows a horn.
A mania or frantic zeal for freedom. [R.] Carlyle.
Not laughing; without laughter.
A device by which a single-phase current is split into two ormore currents differing in phase. It is used in starting single-phaseinduction motors.
Of the same blood; related by birth; descended from the sameparent or ancestor. Shak.
Furnished with a dewlap.
